          "body": "God opens His case not with abstract accusation but with a visual argument: 'You yourselves have seen all the calamity I brought on Jerusalem and the cities of Judah; and behold, this day they are in ruins' (44:2). The ruins of Jerusalem are the evidence. The legal logic is straightforward: the disaster was announced by prophets (44:4), refused by the people (44:5), and then executed by God (44:6). That sequence has already completed itself once. Now the same people in Egypt are doing the same thing (44:8). The rhetorical question of 44:7 — 'Why are you doing great harm to yourselves?' — is not puzzlement but indictment. The word *nephesh* (souls, yourselves) makes the self-destruction personal: they are cutting off their own life. Most devastating of all is 44:10: 'they have not become contrite even to this day.' The destruction of their nation, the loss of Jerusalem and the temple, the death of thousands, the exile of the educated classes to Babylon, and their own desperate flight to Egypt — none of it produced *dakah*, brokenness. This is the chapter's diagnostic sentence and the precondition for everything that follows."
