          "title": "The people's counter-theology — inverted causation (44:15-19)",
          "body": "The community's response in 44:16-18 is one of the most extraordinary passages in prophetic literature. They do not merely ignore Jeremiah; they issue a formal counter-argument. Their empirical case is: correlation between queen-of-heaven worship and prosperity, correlation between stopping that worship and disaster. 'When we burned incense to the queen of heaven, we had plenty of food and were well off and saw no misfortune. But since we stopped, we have lacked everything and have met our end by the sword and famine' (44:17-18). This is not thoughtless superstition but organized historical interpretation — the same events, the same timeline, the same cause-and-effect logic, reaching the diametrically opposite conclusion from God's. The women's addition in 44:19 is significant: they assert that the worship was domestically authorized by their husbands, not a unilateral female deviation. This was household religion, sanctioned at every level. The queen of heaven cult identified here is almost certainly Ishtar/Astarte — the astral goddess of love and fertility whose cult had penetrated Judah's royal circles before the exile (cf. Jeremiah 7:18, where families collectively bake cakes for the queen of heaven). Their argument is a theological mirror image of Jeremiah's: same history, inverted reading."
