          "title": "Jeremiah's rebuttal — the true causal chain (44:20-23)",
          "body": "Jeremiah's counter-rebuttal in 44:20-23 is compressed and forensic. He does not dispute their experience; he disputes their causation. Did the Lord not remember your idolatry in Jerusalem? (44:21). Yes — and it was precisely that remembrance that produced the disaster (44:22). The calamity they are attributing to stopping their idolatry is in fact the delayed full consequence of the idolatry they now wish to resume. Verse 23 states the because-therefore chain with maximum grammatical clarity: 'Because you have burned sacrifices and have sinned against the Lord and not obeyed the voice of the Lord or walked in His law, His statutes or His testimonies, therefore this calamity has befallen you, as it is this day.' Every element — idolatry, disobedience, refusal to walk in Torah — maps directly onto a consequence. The passage functions as an exegetical correction: the people have misread the data of their own history because they have dismissed the theological framework that would have allowed them to read it correctly. Without Yahweh's self-disclosure, providence is uninterpretable — or worse, interpretable in ways that confirm chosen idolatry."
